'''Lucy Jones''' is a British painter and printmaker who was born in London in 1955.<ref name=LBarnett>{{cite web |author=Laura Barnett|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2007/apr/17/art |title=Portrait of the artist, Lucy Jones |date=17 April 2007|accessdate=23 March 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref> She was born with [[cerebral palsy]]. Jones is represented by [[Flowers Gallery]].<ref>[https://www.flowersgallery.com/artists/view/lucy-jones Flowers Gallery. Lucy Jones]</ref>
== Career == Jones was educated at the [[King Alfred School, London]] and studied at the [[Byam Shaw School of Art]] between 1975 and 1977.<ref name="BuckmanVol2">{{cite book|author=David Buckman|publisher=Art Dictionaries Ltd|year=2006|title=Artists in Britain Since 1945 Vol 2, M to Z |ISBN=0 953260 95 X}}</ref> From 1976 to 1979 Jones studied at the [[Camberwell School of Art]] and then at the [[Royal College of Arts]] from 1979 until 1982.<ref name=JWullschlager/> In 1982 she won the Prix de Rome prize which allowed her to study at the British School in Rome for two years.<ref name="BuckmanVol2"/> Jones had her first solo exhibition, at the Flowers Gallery,in 1987.<ref name=JWullschlager/> She has exhibited her work extensively in the UK and abroad.<ref name=JWullschlager>{{cite web |author=Jackie Wullschlager|url=https://www.ft.com/content/640a1082-82a6-11e3-9d7e-00144feab7de#slide |title=Lucy Jones at Kings Place, London |date=24 January 2014|accessdate=23 March 2018|work=The Financial Times}}</ref> Her work is in many public and private collections including the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York.<ref>[http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/485213 Lucy Jones. Metropolitan Museum of Art]</ref>
