{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Use Australian English|date=October 2014}} {{Infobox sportsperson| | name = Sam Carter |image = File:XXXX15 - Samuel Carter - 3b - 2016 Team processing.jpg |caption = 2016 Australian Paralympic Team Portrait | headercolor = green | textcolor = yellow | nationality = {{AUS}} | club = | collegeteam = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|08|06|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Toowoomba, Queensland]] | height = | weight = | medaltemplates= {{MedalCountry| {{AUS}} }} {{MedalSport|Men's [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]}} {{MedalCompetition| [[IPC Grand Prix ]]}} - {{MedalGold| 2015 Brisbane|Men's 100m Wheelchair}} {{MedalSilver| 2015 Brisbane |Men's 400m Wheelchair}} }}
'''Samuel "Sam" Harrison Carter''' is a Paralympic athlete, who competes in 100m, 200m, 400m [[T54 (classification)|T54]] events.<ref name=ipcbio>{{cite web|title=Samuel Harrison Carter|url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/TheASP.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=904070|website=IPC Bio|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> He has represented Australia at the [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympics]] in athletics.<ref name="athletics">{{cite web|title=Australian Paralympic Athletics Team announced|url=https://www.paralympic.org.au/11564-2/|website=Australian Paralympic Committee News, 2 August 2016|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=chronsrint />
==Personal== Carter was born on 6 August 1991,<ref name=athhis>{{cite web |title=Sam Carter |url=http://athhistory.imgstg.com/athletes/athlete6435.htm |website=athhistory.imgstg.com |publisher=Australia Athletics Historical Results |accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> he has [[Spina bifida]].<ref name=APCbio>{{cite web|title=Sam Carter|url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/sam-carter-0|website=APC|accessdate=5 August 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150228133522/http://paralympic.org.au/team/sam-carter-0|archivedate=28 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He attended [[Harristown State High School]] in [[Queensland]].<ref name=chrongoal>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.thechronicle.com.au/news/apn-coach-sets-sam-summe/2371/ |title=Coach sets Sam summer goal &#124; Toowoomba Chronicle |publisher=Thechronicle.com.au |date=2005-09-07 |accessdate=2015-08-11}}</ref> Before becoming a wheelchair racer, Carter was actively engaged in sport in particular swimming and wheelchair basketball.<ref name=ipcbio /> He then attended a try day held by Queensland Sporting Wheelies in 2001.<ref name=APCbio /> At the event Carter met Paralympian [[Geoff Trappett]] who won gold in the T54 and encouraged Carter to become involved in wheelchair racing.<ref name=ipcbio /><ref name=APCbio /> His sporting hero is [[Kurt Fearnley]].<ref name=ipcbio /> When not training he is studying law at the [[University of Southern Queensland]] and playing his guitar.<ref name=ipcbio />
==Sporting career== Carter began competing in 2003 as a junior athlete.<ref name=APCbio /> He has worked with [[Andrew Dawes (coach)|Andrew Dawes]] and [[Louise Sauvage]] to improve his performance and trained with wheelchair athlete Sybilla Austin.<ref name=chrongoal /> In 2008 he broke national age records for the 100m, 200m and 400m in wheelchair racing.<ref name=sportdreams>{{cite web|title=Sam Carter - Wheelchair racing|url=http://www.sportingdreams.org.au/portfolio/sam-carter-wheelchair-racing/|website=Sporting Dreams|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref> He went on to become the 200m junior world champion.<ref name=chronsrint>{{cite web|last1=Braban|first1=Tim|title=Sprint champ aims for world title|url=http://www.thechronicle.com.au/news/junior-sprint-champ-sam-carter-wheelchair-athlete/713978/|website=The Chronicle|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref> One of his career highlights was winning gold in the 100m at the 2009 Junior Athletics World Championships.<ref name=APCbio /> In 2011 Carter made the transition into adult competitions<ref name=sundaily>{{cite web|last1=Weir|first1=Kirsty|title=Carter eyes Paralympics|url=http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/sam-carter-eyes-paralympics-airport-marathon/897580/|website=Sunshine Coast Daily|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref> where, he has competed against wheelchair racers such as [[David Weir (wheelchair athlete)|David Weir]] and [[Marcel Hug]].<ref name=APCbio /> Carter represented Australia at the [[2011 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Christchurch]]<ref name=apcnews>{{cite web|title=Wheelchair track and road team burns the track in Switzerland|url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/news/wheelchair-track-and-road-team-burns-track-switzerland|website=APC|accessdate=5 August 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401095822/http://paralympic.org.au/news/wheelchair-track-and-road-team-burns-track-switzerland|archivedate=1 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> in the T54 100m, 200m and 400m.<ref name=ipcbio /> He also competed in the 2011 Gold Coast Wheelchair Half Marathon which he won.<ref>{{cite web|title=Previous Winners|url=http://goldcoastmarathon.com.au/results/winners/|website=Gold Coast Marathon|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> In 2013 Carter was selected to represent Australia, in the T54 100m, 200m and 400m at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Lyon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Paralympians set to turn Classic into Wheel Deal|url=http://nswathletics.org.au/Results/paralympians-set-to-turn-classic-into-wheel-deal|website=NSW Athletics|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>] He placed 6th and 5th in the T54 100m and 200m respectively.<ref name=ipcbio /> He won gold and silver at the 2015 [[Brisbane]] IPC Grand Prix in the T54 100m and 400m respectively.<ref name=qldath>{{cite web|title=IPC Grand Prix wrap up|url=http://qldathletics.org.au/News/ipc-grand-prix-wrap-up|website=QLD Athletics|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>
At the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in [[Doha]], Carter finished sixth in the Men's 100 m T54, fifth in the Men's 200 m and sixteenth in the Men's 400 m T54.<ref name=ipcbio/>
At the [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Rio Paralympics]], Carter finished sixth in the Men's 100 m T54 and was ranked 15th in the Men's 400 m T54.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sam Carter|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/athlete/samuel-carter|website=Rio Paralympics Official site|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref>
==Recognition== In 2009 Carter won the Sports Darling Downs senior rookie of the year.<ref name=sportsdowns>{{cite web|title=2009 Presentation Dinner|url=http://www.sportsdarlingdowns.org/pres2009.htm|website=Sports Darling Downs|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> Recently, Carter has been named as having podium potential by [[Athletics Australia]] in the T54 100m, 400m and 4 × 400 m.<ref name=Athaus>{{cite web|title=ATHLETICS AUSTRALIA NASS; PARA-ATHLETICS HIGH PERFORMANCE PROGRAM|url=http://athletics.com.au/High-Performance/NASS/Para-Athletes|website=Athletics Australia|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> As of 2014 Carter receives a scholarship from the [[Queensland Academy of Sport]]<ref name=QLDacd>{{cite web|title=High Performance Program - Athletics|url=http://www.qasport.qld.gov.au/sports/athletics.html|website=Queensland Academy of Sport|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> and a grant from the [[Australian Institute of Sport]].<ref name=ascgrant>{{cite web|title=Grant Funding Report|url=http://www.ausport.gov.au/supporting/funding/grants_and_scholarships/grant_funding_report?FundingCategory=DAS&RecipientName=samuel+carter&RecipientType=&RecipientState=&FinancialYear=All&Submit=Filter|website=ASC|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>
