{{Other people|William Edwards}}

'''William Edwards''' (1770–1851) was an [[United States|American]] inventor, grandson of [[Jonathan Edwards (theologian)|Jonathan Edwards, the elder]]. He was born in [[Elizabeth, New Jersey|Elizabethtown]], [[New Jersey]]. He introduced a valuable improvement in the manufacture of [[leather]], whereby tanning was accomplished in a quarter of the usual time.  He invented machines which greatly advanced the production of leather in America.<ref>White, James Terry. [https://books.google.com/books?id=-t4DAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA225 "The National Cyclopaedia of American Biography"], p. 225. Accessed December 9, 2007.</ref>

